               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18370814-name-1116" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18370814-name-1116" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370814-name-1116" type="surname" value="SIMMONDS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18370814-name-1116" type="given" value="EMMA"></interp>EMMA SIMMONDS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am thirteen years old, and live in Pilgrim's-lane, Hampstead, with my father, William Simmonds. On Wednesday after noon, the 9th of August, I saw a man with matches at the kitchen window, he was about the prisoner's size, and dressed like him—I shook my head to say I did not want any—my mother's shawl hung on the bannisters of the stairs, and the back-door of the house was open—I missed the shawl directly the man was gone—I have since seen it in possession of Eaton, the constable.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18370814-name-1117" type="witnessName">
